post_text:
National Hispanic Heritage Month is a month-long United States holiday to celebrate the contributions, cultures, and history of people living in the U.S. with ancestors from Mexico, Spain, Central and South America, and the Caribbean Islands.

This month is full of significant historic events for much of Latin America, such as:

-September 15th is celebrated as Independence Day in Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, and Nicaragua,
-September 16th is Independence day for Mexico,
-September 18th is Independence day for Chile, and
-September 21st is Independence day for Belize

Luling ISD recognizes and celebrates this amazing month!

post_text:
FOOD SERVICE UPDATE!
The USDA recently extended the Summer Food Service Program. Due to this extension, beginning tomorrow Luling ISD will be providing FREE BREAKFAST AND LUNCH TO ALL CHILDREN 0-18 YEARS OLD!

The program is scheduled to expire on Dec. 31 or when funds run out, whichever happens first.

The district will serve students attending onsite at all buildings. At-home learners and other children in the community are able to pick up the free meals outside the High School Cafeteria from 9am-10am. Students will be able to pick up breakfast and lunch at the same time.

When funds run out, the district will go back to the National School Breakfast and Lunch programs and students will be charged according to their eligibility.

The district will serve students attending onsite at all buildings. At-home learners and other children in the community are able to pick up the free meals outside the High School Cafeteria from 9am-10am. Students will be able to pick up breakfast and lunch at the same time.

When funds run out, the district will go back to the National School Breakfast and Lunch programs and students will be charged according to their eligibility.

At approximately 12:15 p.m., Luling ISD received a report of possible suspicious activity in the vicinity of the campuses. As a precautionary measure, campuses were placed in Lockout (Secure) mode. Instruction inside the buildings continued, but transitions between buildings were eliminated. Upon receipt of an ‚ÄúAll Clear‚Äù from local and area law enforcement, the Lockout was removed and campuses resumed normal operations. For additional information regarding Luling ISD‚Äôs emergency response procedures utilizing the Standard Response Protocol, please see the attachment.

post_text:
September is National Suicide Prevention Awareness month.

#Bethe1To Ask #NationalSuicidePreventionAwarenessMonth

"Every day in the United States friends, family and co-workers struggle with emotional pain. And, for some, it's too difficult to talk about the pain, thoughts of suicide and the need for help. Though the warning signs can be subtle, they are there. By recognizing these signs, knowing how to start a conversation and where to turn for help, you have the power to make a difference and instill hope‚Äì the power to save a life."

post_text: Luling ISD is pleased to announce a generous donation of $3,000 made today by the Society of St. Vincent de Paul. $2,500 has been earmarked to assist with technology expenses and another $500 will be used to enrich and extend opportunities for second grade students at Shanklin Elementary. Joining Superintendent Warren today were Irene Moore, Donna Martinez, and Gerianne Canny. Community support during these challenging and uncertain times is very much appreciated. Thank you members of the Society of St. Vincent de Paul!

post_text:
Luling Junior High Football Update:

GGJH will start football practice on August 17th. Student-athletes will practice in the morning and be released in time to return home and engage in remote learning. A set time schedule will be sent out on August 10th.
Returning 8th graders must complete the medical history paperwork available on the school athletics website, or available at the fieldhouse from Coach Yager. Incoming 7th graders must complete the medical history paperwork AND receive a physical from a physician/clinic of their choice. This is mandatory for 7th grade athletes. Please complete this task in time for practice.
If you have any questions or concerns contact Coach Yager- audrey.yager@luling.txed.net or Coach Keilman- benjamin.keilman@luling.txed.net.
Thank you and Go Eagles

post_text:
EXCITING NEWS FOR OUR COMMUNITY!
Luling will have its first Central Texas Food Bank Mobile Food Distribution on Monday, August 17, 2020 at the Zedler Mill parking lot. Residents will remain in their car as they drive through the distribution site for their food to be placed in their trunk. See attached flyer for full details, and please feel free to share/post.

The next service date for the Luling Food Bank will be August 11, 2020, 8am-12pm, which is also a drive-through service.

The Angel Food Pantry at Nolan Terrace Apartments in Luling is on Wednesdays, 9am-3pm and Meadow Park Village on Thursdays, 9am-3pm, (available by appointment.) Call or text Christy at 830-313-5858 to schedule or for more info.

post_text:
June 14, 2020 - 5:10pm

Dear Parents and Staff,
Luling ISD has been notified that a Luling High School student who attended the girls‚Äô strength camp on Monday, June 8th has tested positive for COVID-19. The student did not attend the strength camp the remainder of the week.

Coaches enforced all UIL guidelines during practice, however due to CDC guidelines for schools, the girls‚Äô strength camp has been cancelled for the next two weeks. The two coaches who were present during Monday‚Äôs practice will self-monitor at home for the next 14 days.

If your child attended the strength camp on Monday the 8th, we advise that you monitor her health, follow the CDC guidelines for people who have had close contact, and contact your primary care physician if she develops symptoms.

The district will remain transparent with our families and will continue to take necessary precautions in order to maintain the health and safety of our students, their families, and our staff.

Sincerely,
Erin Warren
Superintendent

post_text:
The 2020 Census is happening now. You can complete your questionnaire online, by phone, or by mail.

Visit my2020census.gov to begin.

The Census Bureau is bound by Title 13 of the U.S. Code to keep your information confidential.

This law protects your answers to the 2020 Census. Under Title 13, the Census Bureau cannot release any identifiable information about you, your home, or your business, even to law enforcement agencies. The law ensures that your private data is protected and that your answers cannot be used against you by any government agency or court.

Dear LISD Staff,
Every staff member is an educator. No matter what your job description says, at the end of the day, you are working to provide an education to students. And all of us know that this job is so much more than imparting knowledge. What you do for kids is unparalleled. Even though our year with them was short, you made a difference in their lives. I appreciate you.

Love,
Mrs. Warren

GRADING GUIDELINES UPDATE - APRIL 21st

TEA has mandated that districts progress monitor student performance on remote learning. This means that students must return specific assignments and we must grade them. Student performance on these assignments will be reflected on their final report card.

Last night the Board approved our proposed changes to the grading guidelines for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. We believe these new guidelines will allow us to measure a students' mastery of the district curriculum, provide timely and meaningful feedback to students and parents, and allow for multiple opportunities for students to demonstrate mastery of learning while at home.
https://www.luling.txed.net/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=1699244&type=d&pREC_ID=1861555

Starting Monday, April 20, PBS will offer educational programming on its main channel (18.1) in the place of the normal PBS KIDS broadcast (which will still be available on the 18.4 24hr PBS KIDS channel). The new schedule will run 6am - 5pm, Monday through Friday, with this breakdown:

Grade PreK-3: Watch 6 a.m to 8 a.m.
Grades 4-8: Watch 8 a.m. to 1 p.m.
Grades 9-12: Watch 1 p.m. to 5 p.m.

PBS's aim is to offer a regular schedule of educational content on TV when students are not able to connect directly to teachers or schools through other means (computers, tablets, etc.).

**UPDATE TO MEAL PICK-UP PROCESS**

In our continued effort to reduce exposure, we are making changes to our food distribution processes.

Starting Monday, March 30th, the grab-and-go meals will be available from 9am-11am outside of the high school cafeteria. Students will be given two meals to take with them.

The district will begin delivering meals via bus routes starting Monday to students who normally ride the bus. Deliveries will happen on Mondays (4 meals) and Wednesdays (6 meals). We attempted to contact all bus riders to communicate this process. If you were not contacted, and your child rides the bus, please email ddietz@luling.txed.net.

We are working on a delivery option for all students, and will communicate that process once it is finalized.

COVID-19 UPDATE - March 14 - 1:15pm

LULING ISD CAMPUSES WILL REMAIN CLOSED UNTIL March 23, 2020.

Out of an abundance of caution, LISD will extend Spring Break for another week. While there are still no confirmed cases in our community, administration has made this decision in the best interest of students and staff.

All Luling students will be eligible for "grab and go" breakfast and lunch for the week of March 16th - 20th. Details on where meals can be picked up and the hours available will be forthcoming.

Administration has begun working on an instructional support plan for our students. Information related to this plan will be sent out as soon as it is finalized.

We do not yet know if students will need to make up this time. We also do not know what the next steps will be after this initial closing. Therefore, please continue to watch our Facebook page and website (www.luling.txed.net) for additional information as it is available.

Sincerely,
Erin Warren
Superintendent

text:
COVID-19 UPDATE:
All student and staff travel is cancelled through April 3rd. This includes field trips, activities, and professional development. We will continue to monitor and provide updates.

Daily calls with the Commissioner of Education and Texas Superintendents started today. Guidance is being provided on school closures and student and staff safety. We appreciate your patience and understanding.

post_text:
COVID-19 UPDATE:
All UIL events have been cancelled.

To support the health and safety of our students and communities, the University Interscholastic League (UIL) is suspending all UIL sanctioned contests due to the outbreak of COVID-19 (Coronavirus) in Texas. Effective March 16, all UIL interscholastic competition is suspended through March 29.
Rehearsals and practices may be held at the discretion of the local school district.
As this is a fluid situation, the UIL will continue to follow the direction of state and local officials to monitor this situation and will make additional announcements as needed. Please continue to check the UIL website and social media accounts for further updates.

The Luling Eagles Powerlifting Teams traveled to Karnes City on Feb 8th for the KC ISD Invitational meet.

The girls team placed 2nd overall with 29 points. Abigail Reyes placed 4th in the 97lb weight class with a total of 305lbs, McKenzie Dees placed 2nd in the 105‚Äôs with a total of 525lbs, Raylynn Brown placed 1st in the 198‚Äôs with a total of 645lbs, Victoria Escobedo placed 3rd in the 259‚Äôs with a total of 735lbs, Yadira Torrez placed 2nd in the 259‚Äôs with a total of 740lbs, and Julia Rios placed 1st in the 259‚Äôs with 785lbs.

Anthony Gonzalez placed 3rd in the 114‚Äôs with a total of 580lbs, Tanner Tucker placed 3rd in the 123‚Äôs with a total of 710lbs.

This was the Eagles third meet of the season.
The boys and girls team each have one more meet to qualify for regionals. We have 1 boy currently qualifying for regionals and 8 girls. The Lady Eagles‚Äô next meet will be at San Marcos high school on Feb 22th at 9am and the Boys on the 29th at Del Valle High School"

Tomorrow is Wear ORANGE Day in support of stopping Teen Dating Violence.

Come on, Luling Eagles, wear ORANGE tomorrow!

post_text:
The Luling ISD Spotlight Staff Member for December is Mr. Robert Broadway!
Mr. Broadway is a dedicated and caring member of the Luling ISD family. He has safely driven our students to and from school since 2015. Mr. Broadway has a huge heart for kids and is frequently heard saying, "Whatever it takes, let me know I will get them there." Mr. Broadway is the first employee students see in the morning, and he sets their day up well with a smile and a ‚Äògood morning.‚Äô He knows each of his riders by their first names and has spent time to get to know them. When one of our families suffered a tragedy, Mr. Broadway was the first person in the district to donate money and clothing. He is an advocate for our district and we are so lucky that he is a Luling Eagle!

Hello, fellow Luling-ites! Please spread the word that Luling ISD will honor three outstanding Distinguished Alumni tonight, beginning with a 6:00 P.M. reception at the CLC, followed by ceremonies to officially induct them into our LHS Hall of Fame at the football game. Please join us at 6:00 to honor the following Eagles for their success and example to our youth and community! We are proud to call them part of the Luling ISD family!

Marques Roberts - Operational Manager for Hermann Memorial Hospital System, founder of #headdownpushing, published author, and inspirational speaker

Rose Chase Smith - Founder & CEO of BLACK WOMEN IN BUSINESS,Co-Founder of BLACK MEN IN BUSINESS, Best Selling author and editor, Leadership & Business Coach, Community Organizer

Dr. Gregory Scott Weiner - Provost and Academic Vice President and Associate Professor of Political Science at Assumption College in Worcester, Maine; widely published writer of books, articles, and reviews.

post_text:
Tomorrow, October 23rd is National Unity Day. All students and staff are asked to wear orange to show their commitment to end bullying.

Make it ORANGE and make it end! What are your true colors when it comes to bullying? If you care about safe and supportive schools and communities make your color ORANGE on Unity Day. That‚Äôs the day everyone can come together ‚Äì in schools, communities, and online ‚Äì and send one large ORANGE message of support, hope, and unity to show that we are together against bullying and united for kindness, acceptance and inclusion.
Individuals across the nation, and even world-wide, can participate in Unity Day.

Parents, community members, students, and staff are meeting right now about the district‚Äôs strategic plan. Thirty-two people worked for 608 hours last spring to create a 5-year plan. Our big areas of focus are:
1. High Expectations
2. High Quality Curriculum and Instruction
3. Staff Recruitment and Retention
4. Internal and External Communication

All of these people have volunteered their time to help the district continue to make improvements! Amazing!

post_text:
September 23-27 is Start With Hello Week created by the Sandy Hook Promise organization. During this week, thousands of schools across the U.S. will participate in this effort with the common goal of bringing attention to the growing epidemic of social isolation.
We try to promote connectedness and inclusion at our schools and we try to identify lonely students who are showing signs of social isolation. Here are the activities for the week:

Monday - Start With Hello Video Introduction
Tuesday - Say Hello In a New Language
Wednesday - Wall of Kindness Post It Notes
Thursday - Start With Hello Chalk Day
Friday - Wear Green

Gifted & Talented Student Referral Packets Available Beginning October 1st

Luling Independent School District is now taking student referrals from the faculty, staff, and community for our Gifted and Talented program. If you would like to refer a student for this program, you may pick up a referral form from the front office of your child‚Äôs campus beginning October 1st. Please return the completed form to the front office no later than January 10, 2020 for kindergarten
and first grade students, and no later than February 28 for second through twelfth grade students. If you have any questions or comments about the referral or nominating process in Luling ISD, please contact Glenda Thacker at 830-875-3191 ext. 1002.

post_text: From September 23 to September 27, Luling ISD will be hosting a school security training in conjunction with the Caldwell County Sheriff‚Äôs Office. This training is focused on conducting campus/facility assessments and as such there will be no tactical movements or techniques demonstrated or taught. Community members may notice an increased presence of law enforcement at the school including officers (uniformed and plainclothes) as well as marked and unmarked vehicles from local and surrounding jurisdictions. We are committed to making our schools as safe as possible and trainings like this provide a great opportunity to foster the vital partnerships necessary for safe communities. If you have any questions, please contact Detective Jeff Ferry at 512-398-6777 ext. 4516 or jferry@caldwellcountysheriff.com
